<p>This flowchart was created with <tt><a href="http://search.cpan.org/perldoc?App:Asciio">App:Asciio</a></tt>, a little tool that came out this spring. In addition to jokes and social commentary, it's rather useful for prototyping program design or documenting complex class hierarchies. The program is rather inutitive; except that "help" is <span style="font-style: italic">k</span> for "keyboard map." Just start clicking and banging away as I did and you can turn something out fairly quickly, without even RTFM. Even though arrows try to be rather intelligent&mdash;they initialy exit the current ballon from bottom and bend right, automagically connecting to any nearby balloon with a free handle&mdash;they can be a little difficult to orient cleanly.</p>
<p>Like many modern applications, <tt>Asciio</tt> autodetects what format to save as based on file extension: <a href="mod21.txt">text/plain</a> for <tt>.txt</tt>, and otherwise a <a href="mod21.asciio">binary format</a>. The binary format is necessary to permit later editing of a chart, since <tt>Asciio</tt>'s author hasn't yet perfected an ASCII flow-chart parser. Another missing function is the ability to insert art from an existing file, though <a href="http://acme.com/software/overlay/">overlay</a> can serve a similar function.</p>
